<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,1221,1956]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,329,1781,1807]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Comment.</emphasis>
The adult females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hodgson &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2002" box="[595,732,1781,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Eriococcidae" genus="Chilechiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[595,732,1781,1806]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Chilechiton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have several unusual or unique features, namely: (i) vulva between abdominal segments VI and VII (only shared by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller &amp; Gonzalez" authorityYear="1976" box="[868,1012,1819,1844]" class="Insecta" family="Eriococcidae" genus="Icelococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[868,1012,1819,1844]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Icelococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and perhaps 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hempel" authorityYear="1937" box="[1178,1369,1819,1844]" class="Insecta" family="Eriococcidae" genus="Neotectococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1178,1369,1819,1844]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Neotectococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (ii) spinose setae in a dense line around margin, each rather clearly differentiated from dorsal spinose setae; and (iii) C-shaped markings on the dorsal surface of each anal lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,1221,1956]" box="[198,823,1930,1956]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,433,1930,1956]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">First-instar nymph</emphasis>
